[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The classic textbook example of the use of backtracking is the eight queens puzzle, that asks for all arrangements of eight chess queens on a standard chessboard so that no queen attacks any other.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] In the common backtracking approach, the partial candidates are arrangements of *k* queens in the first *k* rows of the board, all in different rows and columns.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Any partial solution that contains two mutually attacking queens can be abandoned.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Backtracking can be applied only for problems which admit the concept of a "partial candidate solution" and a relatively quick test of whether it can possibly be completed to a valid solution.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] It is useless, for example, for locating a given value in an unordered table.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] When it is applicable, however, backtracking is often much faster than brute-force enumeration of all complete candidates, since it can eliminate many candidates with a single test.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Backtracking is an important tool for solving constraint satisfaction problems, such as crosswords, verbal arithmetic, Sudoku, and many other puzzles.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] It is often the most convenient technique for parsing, for the knapsack problem and other combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] It is also the program execution strategy used in the programming languages Icon, Planner and Prolog.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Backtracking depends on user-given "black box procedures" that define the problem to be solved, the nature of the partial candidates, and how they are extended into complete candidates.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] It is therefore a metaheuristic rather than a specific algorithm – although, unlike many other meta-heuristics, it is guaranteed to find all solutions to a finite problem in a bounded amount of time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The term "backtrack" was coined by American mathematician D.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The pioneer string-processing language SNOBOL (1962) may have been the first to provide a built-in general backtracking facility.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The backtracking algorithm enumerates a set of *partial candidates* that, in principle, could be *completed* in various ways to give all the possible solutions to the given problem.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The backtracking algorithm traverses this search tree recursively, from the root down, in depth-first order.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] At each node *c*, the algorithm checks whether *c* can be completed to a valid solution.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] If it cannot, the whole sub-tree rooted at *c* is skipped (*pruned*).
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Otherwise, the algorithm (1) checks whether *c* itself is a valid solution, and if so reports it to the user; and (2) recursively enumerates all sub-trees of *c*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The two tests and the children of each node are defined by user-given procedures.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Therefore, the *actual search tree* that is traversed by the algorithm is only a part of the potential tree.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The total cost of the algorithm is the number of nodes of the actual tree times the cost of obtaining and processing each node.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] This fact should be considered when choosing the potential search tree and implementing the pruning test.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] In order to apply backtracking to a specific class of problems, one must provide the data *P* for the particular instance of the problem that is to be solved, and six procedural parameters, *root*, *reject*, *accept*, *first*, *next*, and *output*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] *reject*(*P*,*c*): return *true* only if the partial candidate *c* is not worth completing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] *accept*(*P*,*c*): return *true* if *c* is a solution of *P*, and *false* otherwise.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] *first*(*P*,*c*): generate the first extension of candidate *c*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] *next*(*P*,*s*): generate the next alternative extension of a candidate, after the extension *s*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] *output*(*P*,*c*): use the solution *c* of *P*, as appropriate to the application.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The *reject* procedure should be a Boolean-valued function that returns *true* only if it is certain that no possible extension of *c* is a valid solution for *P*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] If the procedure cannot reach a definite conclusion, it should return *false*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] An incorrect *true* result may cause the *backtrack* procedure to miss some valid solutions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The procedure may assume that *reject*(*P*,*t*) returned *false* for every ancestor *t* of *c* in the search tree.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] On the other hand, the efficiency of the backtracking algorithm depends on *reject* returning *true* for candidates that are as close to the root as possible.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] If *reject* always returns *false*, the algorithm will still find all solutions, but it will be equivalent to a brute-force search.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The *accept* procedure should return *true* if *c* is a complete and valid solution for the problem instance *P*, and *false* otherwise.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] It may assume that the partial candidate *c* and all its ancestors in the tree have passed the *reject* test.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The general pseudo-code above does not assume that the valid solutions are always leaves of the potential search tree.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] In other words, it admits the possibility that a valid solution for *P* can be further extended to yield other valid solutions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The *first* and *next* procedures are used by the backtracking algorithm to enumerate the children of a node *c* of the tree, that is, the candidates that differ from *c* by a single extension step.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The call *first*(*P*,*c*) should yield the first child of *c*, in some order; and the call *next*(*P*,*s*) should return the next sibling of node *s*, in that order.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Both functions should return a distinctive "NULL" candidate, if the requested child does not exist.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Together, the *root*, *first*, and *next* functions define the set of partial candidates and the potential search tree.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] They should be chosen so that every solution of *P* occurs somewhere in the tree, and no partial candidate occurs more than once.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Moreover, they should admit an efficient and effective *reject* predicate.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The pseudo-code above will call *output* for all candidates that are a solution to the given instance *P*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The algorithm can be modified to stop after finding the first solution, or a specified number of solutions; or after testing a specified number of partial candidates, or after spending a given amount of CPU time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The general constraint satisfaction problem consists in finding a list of integers *x* = (*x*[1], *x*[2], …, *x*[*n*]), each in some range {1, 2, …, *m*}, that satisfies some arbitrary constraint (Boolean function) *F*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] For this class of problems, the instance data *P* would be the integers *m* and *n*, and the predicate *F*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] In a typical backtracking solution to this problem, one could define a partial candidate as a list of integers *c* = (*c*[1], *c*[2], …, *c*[k]), for any *k* between 0 and *n*, that are to be assigned to the first *k* variables *x*[1], *x*[2], …, *x*[*k*].
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The root candidate would then be the empty list ().
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Here *length*(*c*) is the number of elements in the list *c*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The call *reject*(*P*, *c*) should return *true* if the constraint *F* cannot be satisfied by any list of *n* integers that begins with the *k* elements of *c*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] For backtracking to be effective, there must be a way to detect this situation, at least for some candidates *c*, without enumerating all those *m**n* − *k* *n*-tuples.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] In fact, *reject* needs only check those terms that do depend on *x*[*k*], since the terms that depend only on *x*[1], …, *x*[*k* − 1] will have been tested further up in the search tree.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Assuming that *reject* is implemented as above, then *accept*(*P*, *c*) needs only check whether *c* is complete, that is, whether it has *n* elements.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] It is generally better to order the list of variables so that it begins with the most critical ones (i.e. the ones with fewest value options, or which have a greater impact on subsequent choices).
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] One could also allow the *next* function to choose which variable should be assigned when extending a partial candidate, based on the values of the variables already assigned by it.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] Further improvements can be obtained by the technique of constraint propagation.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] In addition to retaining minimal recovery values used in backing up, backtracking implementations commonly keep a variable trail, to record value change history.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] An efficient implementation will avoid creating a variable trail entry between two successive changes when there is no choice point, as the backtracking will erase all of the changes as a single operation.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] An alternative to the variable trail is to keep a timestamp of when the last change was made to the variable.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] The timestamp is compared to the timestamp of a choice point.
[src:nom-parser-rust/backtracking] If the choice point has an associated time later than that of the variable, it is unnecessary to revert the variable when the choice point is backtracked, as it was changed before the choice point occurred.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A **formal grammar** is a set of symbols and the production rules for rewriting some of them into every possible string of a formal language over an alphabet.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A grammar does not describe the meaning of the strings—only their form.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] In applied mathematics, formal language theory is the discipline that studies formal grammars and languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Its applications are found in theoretical computer science, theoretical linguistics, formal semantics, mathematical logic, and other areas.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A formal grammar is a set of rules for rewriting strings, along with a "start symbol" from which rewriting starts.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Therefore, a grammar is usually thought of as a language generator.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] However, it can also be used as the basis for a parser—a function in computing that determines whether a given string belongs to the language or is grammatically incorrect.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] To describe such parsers, formal language theory uses separate formalisms, known as automata theory.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] One result of automata theory is that it is not possible to design a recognizer for certain formal languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Many languages have the meanings of their strings structured according to their syntax—a practice known as compositional semantics.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] In these cases, the first step to describing the meaning of a string is to break it down part by part and look at its analyzed form (known as its parse tree in computer science, and as its deep structure in generative grammar).
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A grammar mainly consists of a set of *production rules*, rewrite rules for transforming strings.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Each rule specifies a replacement of a particular string (its *left-hand side*) with another (its *right-hand side*).
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A rule can be applied to each string that contains its left-hand side and produces a string in which an occurrence of that left-hand side has been replaced with its right-hand side.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Unlike a semi-Thue system, which is wholly defined by these rules, a grammar further distinguishes between two kinds of symbols: *nonterminal* and *terminal* symbols; each left-hand side must contain at least one nonterminal symbol.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] It also distinguishes a special nonterminal symbol, called the *start symbol*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] The language generated by the grammar is defined to be the set of all strings without any nonterminal symbols that can be generated from the string consisting of a single start symbol by (possibly repeated) application of its rules in whatever way possible.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] If there are essentially different ways of generating the same single string, the grammar is said to be ambiguous.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] In the following examples, the terminal symbols are *a* and *b*, and the start symbol is *S*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] then we start with *S*, and can choose a rule to apply to it.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] If we choose rule 1, we obtain the string *aSb*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] If we then choose rule 1 again, we replace *S* with *aSb* and obtain the string *aaSbb*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] If we now choose rule 2, we replace *S* with *ba* and obtain the string *aababb*, and are done.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] We can write this series of choices more briefly, using symbols: $S\Rightarrow aSb\Rightarrow aaSbb\Rightarrow aababb$ .
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] The language of the grammar is the infinite set $\{a^{n}bab^{n}\mid n\geq 0\}=\{ba,abab,aababb,aaababbb,\dotsc \}$ , where $a^{k}$ is a repeated k times (and n in particular represents the number of times production rule 1 has been applied).
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] This grammar is context-free (only single nonterminals appear as left-hand sides) and unambiguous.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] This grammar is not context-free due to rule 3 and it is ambiguous due to the multiple ways in which rule 2 can be used to generate sequences of S s.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] However, the language it generates is simply the set of all nonempty strings consisting of a s and/or b s.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] This is easy to see: to generate a b from an S , use rule 2 twice to generate $SSS$ , then rule 1 twice and rule 3 once to produce b .
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] This means we can generate arbitrary nonempty sequences of S s and then replace each of them with a or b as we please.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] That is, each production rule maps from one string of symbols to another, where the first string (the "head") contains an arbitrary number of symbols provided at least one of them is a nonterminal.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A grammar is formally defined as the tuple $(N,\Sigma ,P,S)$ .
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Such a formal grammar is often called a rewriting system or a phrase structure grammar in the literature.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] This grammar defines the language $L(G)=\left\{a^{n}b^{n}c^{n}\mid n\geq 1\right\}$ where $a^{n}$ denotes a string of *n* consecutive a 's.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Thus, the language is the set of strings that consist of 1 or more a 's, followed by the same number of b 's, followed by the same number of c 's.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] When Noam Chomsky first formalized generative grammars in 1956, he classified them into types now known as the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] The difference between these types is that they have increasingly strict production rules and can therefore express fewer formal languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Two important types are *context-free grammars* (Type 2) and *regular grammars* (Type 3).
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] The languages that can be described with such a grammar are called *context-free languages* and *regular languages*, respectively.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Although much less powerful than unrestricted grammars (Type 0), which can in fact express any language that can be accepted by a Turing machine, these two restricted types of grammars are most often used because parsers for them can be efficiently implemented.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] For example, all regular languages can be recognized by a finite-state machine, and for useful subsets of context-free grammars there are well-known algorithms to generate efficient LL parsers and LR parsers to recognize the corresponding languages those grammars generate.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A *context-free grammar* is a grammar in which the left-hand side of each production rule consists of only a single nonterminal symbol.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] This restriction is non-trivial; not all languages can be generated by context-free grammars.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Those that can are called *context-free languages*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A context-free language can be recognized in $O(n^{3})$ time (*see* Big O notation) by an algorithm such as Earley's recogniser and in a sub-cubic time by fast matrix multiplication algorithms.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] That is, for every context-free language, a machine can be built that takes a string as input and determines in $O(n^{3})$ time whether the string is a member of the language, where n is the length of the string.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Deterministic context-free languages is a subset of context-free languages that can be recognized in linear time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] There exist various algorithms that target either this set of languages or some subset of it.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] In regular grammars, the left hand side is again only a single nonterminal symbol, but now the right-hand side is also restricted.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] The right side may be the empty string, or a single terminal symbol, or a single terminal symbol followed by a nonterminal symbol, but nothing else.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] All languages generated by a regular grammar can be recognized in $O(n)$ time by a finite-state machine.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Although in practice, regular grammars are commonly expressed using regular expressions, some forms of regular expression used in practice do not strictly generate the regular languages and do not show linear recognitional performance due to those deviations.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Many extensions and variations on Chomsky's original hierarchy of formal grammars have been developed, both by linguists and by computer scientists, usually either in order to increase their expressive power or in order to make them easier to analyze or parse.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] A recursive grammar is a grammar that contains production rules that are recursive.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] For example, a grammar for a context-free language is left-recursive if there exists a non-terminal symbol *A* that can be put through the production rules to produce a string with *A* as the leftmost symbol.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] An example of recursive grammar is a clause within a sentence separated by two commas.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] All types of grammars in the Chomsky hierarchy can be recursive.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Though there is a tremendous body of literature on parsing algorithms, most of these algorithms assume that the language to be parsed is initially *described* by means of a *generative* formal grammar, and that the goal is to transform this generative grammar into a working parser.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] Strictly speaking, a generative grammar does not in any way correspond to the algorithm used to parse a language, and various algorithms have different restrictions on the form of production rules that are considered well-formed.
[src:nom-parser-rust/formal-grammar] An alternative approach is to formalize the language in terms of an analytic grammar in the first place, which more directly corresponds to the structure and semantics of a parser for the language.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] nom is a parser combinator library with a focus on safe parsing, streaming patterns, and as much as possible zero copy.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] There are a few guides with more details about how to write parsers, or the error management system.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] You can also check out the recipes module that contains examples of common patterns.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] If you are upgrading to nom 5.0, please read the migration document.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] Parser combinators are an approach to parsers that is very different from software like lex and yacc.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] Instead of writing the grammar in a separate syntax and generating the corresponding code, you use very small functions with very specific purposes, like “take 5 bytes”, or “recognize the word ‘HTTP’”, and assemble them in meaningful patterns like “recognize ‘HTTP’, then a space, then a version”.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] The resulting code is small, and looks like the grammar you would have written with other parser approaches.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] It defines a function named `parens` which will recognize a sequence of the character `(`, the longest byte array not containing `)`, then the character `)`, and will return the byte array in the middle.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] This function takes a byte array as input, and tries to consume 4 bytes.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] Writing all the parsers manually, like this, is dangerous, despite Rust’s safety features.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] There are still a lot of mistakes one can make.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] That’s why nom provides a list of functions to help in developing parsers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] Please refer to the “choose a combinator” guide for an exhaustive list of parsers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] See also the rest of the documentation here.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] nom is based on functions that generate parsers, with a signature like this: `(arguments) -> impl Fn(Input) -> IResult<Input, Output, Error>`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] The arguments of a combinator can be direct values (like `take` which uses a number of bytes or character as argument) or even other parsers (like `delimited` which takes as argument 3 parsers, and returns the result of the second one if all are successful).
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] There are higher level patterns, like the **`alt`** combinator, which provides a choice between multiple parsers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] The **`opt`** combinator makes a parser optional.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] There are more complex (and more useful) parsers like tuples, which are used to apply a series of parsers then assemble their results.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] Some of nom’s modules have `streaming` or `complete` submodules.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] They hold different variants of the same combinators.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] A streaming parser assumes that we might not have all of the input data.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] This can happen with some network protocol or large file parsers, where the input buffer can be full and need to be resized or refilled.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] A complete parser assumes that we already have all of the input data.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] This will be the common case with small files that can be read entirely to memory.
[src:nom-parser-rust/latest-nom] Helper trait to convert numbers to usize.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:nom-parser-rust/lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In computer programming, a **parser combinator** is a higher-order function that accepts several parsers as input and returns a new parser as its output.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In this context, a parser is a function accepting strings as input and returning some structure as output, typically a parse tree or a set of indices representing locations in the string where parsing stopped successfully.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Parser combinators enable a recursive descent parsing strategy that facilitates modular piecewise construction and testing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] This parsing technique is called **combinatory parsing**.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Parsers using combinators have been used extensively in the prototyping of compilers and processors for domain-specific languages such as natural-language user interfaces to databases, where complex and varied semantic actions are closely integrated with syntactic processing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In 1989, Richard Frost and John Launchbury demonstrated use of parser combinators to construct natural-language interpreters.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Graham Hutton also used higher-order functions for basic parsing in 1992 and monadic parsing in 1996.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Swierstra also exhibited the practical aspects of parser combinators in 2001.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In 2008, Frost, Hafiz and Callaghan described a set of parser combinators in the functional programming language Haskell that solve the long-standing problem of accommodating left recursion, and work as a complete top-down parsing tool in polynomial time and space.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In any programming language that has first-class functions, parser combinators can be used to combine basic parsers to construct parsers for more complex rules.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] For example, a production rule of a context-free grammar (CFG) may have one or more alternatives and each alternative may consist of a sequence of non-terminal(s) and/or terminal(s), or the alternative may consist of a single non-terminal or terminal or the empty string.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] If a simple parser is available for each of these alternatives, a parser combinator can be used to combine each of these parsers, returning a new parser which can recognise any or all of the alternatives.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In languages that support operator overloading, a parser combinator can take the form of an infix operator, used to glue different parsers to form a complete rule.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Parser combinators thereby enable parsers to be defined in an embedded style, in code which is similar in structure to the rules of the formal grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] As such, implementations can be thought of as executable specifications with all the associated advantages such as readability.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] To keep the discussion relatively straightforward, we discuss parser combinators in terms of *recognizers* only.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] If the input string is of length `#input` and its members are accessed through an index `j`, a recognizer is a parser which returns, as output, a set of indices representing indices at which the parser successfully finished recognizing a sequence of tokens that begin at index `j`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] An empty result set indicates that the recognizer failed to recognize any sequence beginning at index `j`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] There may be multiple distinct ways to parse a string while finishing at the same index, indicating an ambiguous grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Simple recognizers do not acknowledge these ambiguities; each possible finishing index is listed only once in the result set.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] For a more complete set of results, a more complicated object such as a parse tree must be returned.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Consider a highly ambiguous context-free grammar, `s ::= ‘x’ s s | ε`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Using the combinators defined earlier, we can modularly define executable notations of this grammar in a modern functional programming language (e.g., Haskell) as `s = term ‘x’ <*> s <*> s <+> empty`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] When the recognizer `s` is applied at index `2` of the input sequence `x x x x x` it would return a result set `{2,3,4,5}`, indicating that there were matches starting at index 2 and finishing at any index between 2 and 5 inclusive.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Parser combinators, like all recursive descent parsers, are not limited to the context-free grammars and thus do no global search for ambiguities in the LL(*k*) parsing Firstk and Followk sets.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Thus, ambiguities are not known until run-time if and until the input triggers them.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In such cases, the recursive descent parser may default (perhaps unknown to the grammar designer) to one of the possible ambiguous paths, resulting in semantic confusion (aliasing) in the use of the language.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] This leads to bugs by users of ambiguous programming languages, which are not reported at compile-time, and which are introduced not by human error, but by ambiguous grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] The only solution that eliminates these bugs is to remove the ambiguities and use a context-free grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] The simple implementations of parser combinators have some shortcomings, which are common in top-down parsing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Naïve combinatory parsing requires exponential time and space when parsing an ambiguous context-free grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] In 1996, Frost and Szydlowski demonstrated how memoization can be used with parser combinators to reduce the time complexity to polynomial.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Later Frost used monads to construct the combinators for systematic and correct threading of memo-table throughout the computation.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] Like any top-down recursive descent parsing, the conventional parser combinators (like the combinators described above) will not terminate while processing a left-recursive grammar (e.g.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] A recognition algorithm that accommodates ambiguous grammars with direct left-recursive rules is described by Frost and Hafiz in 2006.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] The algorithm curtails the otherwise ever-growing left-recursive parse by imposing depth restrictions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] This extended algorithm accommodates indirect left recursion by comparing its ‘computed context’ with ‘current context’.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parser-combinator] The same authors also described their implementation of a set of parser combinators written in the Haskell language based on the same algorithm.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The term has slightly different meanings in different branches of linguistics and computer science.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Traditional sentence parsing is often performed as a method of understanding the exact meaning of a sentence or word, sometimes with the aid of devices such as sentence diagrams.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] It usually emphasizes the importance of grammatical divisions such as subject and predicate.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Within computational linguistics the term is used to refer to the formal analysis by a computer of a sentence or other string of words into its constituents, resulting in a parse tree showing their syntactic relation to each other, which may also contain semantic information.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Some parsing algorithms generate a *parse forest* or list of parse trees from a string that is syntactically ambiguous.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The term is also used in psycholinguistics when describing language comprehension.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Within computer science, the term is used in the analysis of computer languages, referring to the syntactic analysis of the input code into its component parts in order to facilitate the writing of compilers and interpreters.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The term may also be used to describe a split or separation.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In data analysis, the term is often used to refer to a process extracting desired information from data, e.g., creating a time series signal from a XML document.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The traditional grammatical exercise of parsing, sometimes known as *clause analysis*, involves breaking down a text into its component parts of speech with an explanation of the form, function, and syntactic relationship of each part.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] This is determined in large part from study of the language's conjugations and declensions, which can be quite intricate for heavily inflected languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] To parse a phrase such as "man bites dog" involves noting that the singular noun "man" is the subject of the sentence, the verb "bites" is the third person singular of the present tense of the verb "to bite", and the singular noun "dog" is the object of the sentence.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Techniques such as sentence diagrams are sometimes used to indicate relation between elements in the sentence.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Parsing was formerly central to the teaching of grammar throughout the English-speaking world, and widely regarded as basic to the use and understanding of written language.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In some machine translation and natural language processing systems, written texts in human languages are parsed by computer programs.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Human sentences are not easily parsed by programs, as there is substantial ambiguity in the structure of human language, whose usage is to convey meaning (or semantics) amongst a potentially unlimited range of possibilities, but only some of which are germane to the particular case.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] So an utterance "Man bites dog" versus "Dog bites man" is definite on one detail but in another language might appear as "Man dog bites" with a reliance on the larger context to distinguish between those two possibilities, if indeed that difference was of concern.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] It is difficult to prepare formal rules to describe informal behaviour even though it is clear that some rules are being followed.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In order to parse natural language data, researchers must first agree on the grammar to be used.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The choice of syntax is affected by both linguistic and computational concerns; for instance some parsing systems use lexical functional grammar, but in general, parsing for grammars of this type is known to be NP-complete.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Head-driven phrase structure grammar is another linguistic formalism which has been popular in the parsing community, but other research efforts have focused on less complex formalisms such as the one used in the Penn Treebank.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shallow parsing aims to find only the boundaries of major constituents such as noun phrases.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Another popular strategy for avoiding linguistic controversy is dependency grammar parsing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Most modern parsers are at least partly statistical; that is, they rely on a corpus of training data which has already been annotated (parsed by hand).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] This approach allows the system to gather information about the frequency with which various constructions occur in specific contexts.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] *(See machine learning.)* Approaches which have been used include straightforward PCFGs (probabilistic context-free grammars), maximum entropy, and neural nets.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Most of the more successful systems use *lexical* statistics (that is, they consider the identities of the words involved, as well as their part of speech).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] However such systems are vulnerable to overfitting and require some kind of smoothing to be effective.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Parsing algorithms for natural language cannot rely on the grammar having 'nice' properties as with manually designed grammars for programming languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] As mentioned earlier some grammar formalisms are very difficult to parse computationally; in general, even if the desired structure is not context-free, some kind of context-free approximation to the grammar is used to perform a first pass.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Algorithms which use context-free grammars often rely on some variant of the CYK algorithm, usually with some heuristic to prune away unlikely analyses to save time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] *(See chart parsing.)* However some systems trade speed for accuracy using, e.g., linear-time versions of the shift-reduce algorithm.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] A somewhat recent development has been parse reranking in which the parser proposes some large number of analyses, and a more complex system selects the best option.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In natural language understanding applications, semantic parsers convert the text into a representation of its meaning.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In psycholinguistics, parsing involves not just the assignment of words to categories (formation of ontological insights), but the evaluation of the meaning of a sentence according to the rules of syntax drawn by inferences made from each word in the sentence (known as connotation).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] This normally occurs as words are being heard or read.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Neurolinguistics generally understands parsing to be a function of working memory, meaning that parsing is used to keep several parts of one sentence at play in the mind at one time, all readily accessible to be analyzed as needed.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Because the human working memory has limitations, so does the function of sentence parsing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] This is evidenced by several different types of syntactically complex sentences that demonstrate potential issues for mental parsing of sentences.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The first, and perhaps most well-known, type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is the garden-path sentence.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] These sentences are designed so that the most common interpretation of the sentence appears grammatically faulty, but upon further inspection, these sentences are grammatically sound.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Garden-path sentences are difficult to parse because they contain a phrase or a word with more than one meaning, often their most typical meaning being a different part of speech.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] For example, in the sentence, "the horse raced past the barn fell", raced is initially interpreted as a past tense verb, but in this sentence, it functions as part of an adjective phrase.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Since parsing is used to identify parts of speech, these sentences challenge the parsing ability of the reader.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Another type of sentence that is difficult to parse is an attachment ambiguity, which includes a phrase that could potentially modify different parts of a sentence, and therefore presents a challenge in identifying syntactic relationship (i.e.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] A third type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is center embedding, in which phrases are placed in the center of other similarly formed phrases (i.e.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] "The rat the cat the man hit chased ran into the trap".) Sentences with 2 or in the most extreme cases 3 center embeddings are challenging for mental parsing, again because of ambiguity of syntactic relationship.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Within neurolinguistics there are multiple theories that aim to describe how parsing takes place in the brain.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The opposing, more contemporary model theorizes that within the mind, the processing of a sentence is not modular, or happening in strict sequence.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Rather, it poses that several different syntactic possibilities can be considered at the same time, because lexical access, syntactic processing, and determination of meaning occur in parallel in the brain.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In this way these processes are integrated.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Although there is still much to learn about the neurology of parsing, studies have shown evidence that several areas of the brain might play a role in parsing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] These include the left anterior temporal pole, the left inferior frontal gyrus, the left superior temporal gyrus, the left superior frontal gyrus, the right posterior cingulate cortex, and the left angular gyrus.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Although it has not been absolutely proven, it has been suggested that these different structures might favor either phrase-structure parsing or dependency-structure parsing, meaning different types of parsing could be processed in different ways which have yet to be understood.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Discourse analysis examines ways to analyze language use and semiotic events.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Persuasive language may be called rhetoric.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] A **parser** is a software component that takes input data (typically text) and builds a data structure – often some kind of parse tree, abstract syntax tree or other hierarchical structure, giving a structural representation of the input while checking for correct syntax.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The parsing may be preceded or followed by other steps, or these may be combined into a single step.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The parser is often preceded by a separate lexical analyser, which creates tokens from the sequence of input characters; alternatively, these can be combined in scannerless parsing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Parsers may be programmed by hand or may be automatically or semi-automatically generated by a parser generator.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Parsing is complementary to templating, which produces formatted *output.* These may be applied to different domains, but often appear together, such as the scanf/printf pair, or the input (front end parsing) and output (back end code generation) stages of a compiler.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The input to a parser is typically text in some computer language, but may also be text in a natural language or less structured textual data, in which case generally only certain parts of the text are extracted, rather than a parse tree being constructed.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Parsers range from very simple functions such as scanf, to complex programs such as the frontend of a C++ compiler or the HTML parser of a web browser.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] An important class of simple parsing is done using regular expressions, in which a group of regular expressions defines a regular language and a regular expression engine automatically generating a parser for that language, allowing pattern matching and extraction of text.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In other contexts regular expressions are instead used prior to parsing, as the lexing step whose output is then used by the parser.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In the case of data languages, a parser is often found as the file reading facility of a program, such as reading in HTML or XML text; these examples are markup languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In the case of programming languages, a parser is a component of a compiler or interpreter, which parses the source code of a computer programming language to create some form of internal representation; the parser is a key step in the compiler frontend.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Programming languages tend to be specified in terms of a deterministic context-free grammar because fast and efficient parsers can be written for them.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] For compilers, the parsing itself can be done in one pass or multiple passes – see one-pass compiler and multi-pass compiler.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The implied disadvantages of a one-pass compiler can largely be overcome by adding fix-ups, where provision is made for code relocation during the forward pass, and the fix-ups are applied backwards when the current program segment has been recognized as having been completed.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] An example where such a fix-up mechanism would be useful would be a forward GOTO statement, where the target of the GOTO is unknown until the program segment is completed.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In this case, the application of the fix-up would be delayed until the target of the GOTO was recognized.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Conversely, a backward GOTO does not require a fix-up, as the location will already be known.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Context-free grammars are limited in the extent to which they can express all of the requirements of a language.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Informally, the reason is that the memory of such a language is limited.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The grammar cannot remember the presence of a construct over an arbitrarily long input; this is necessary for a language in which, for example, a name must be declared before it may be referenced.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] More powerful grammars that can express this constraint, however, cannot be parsed efficiently.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Thus, it is a common strategy to create a relaxed parser for a context-free grammar which accepts a superset of the desired language constructs (that is, it accepts some invalid constructs); later, the unwanted constructs can be filtered out at the semantic analysis (contextual analysis) step.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The following example demonstrates the common case of parsing a computer language with two levels of grammar: lexical and syntactic.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The first stage is the token generation, or lexical analysis, by which the input character stream is split into meaningful symbols defined by a grammar of regular expressions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] For example, a calculator program would look at an input such as "`12 * (3 + 4)^2`" and split it into the tokens `12`, `*`, `(`, `3`, `+`, `4`, `)`, `^`, `2`, each of which is a meaningful symbol in the context of an arithmetic expression.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The lexer would contain rules to tell it that the characters `*`, `+`, `^`, `(` and `)` mark the start of a new token, so meaningless tokens like "`12*`" or "`(3`" will not be generated.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The next stage is parsing or syntactic analysis, which is checking that the tokens form an allowable expression.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] This is usually done with reference to a context-free grammar which recursively defines components that can make up an expression and the order in which they must appear.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] However, not all rules defining programming languages can be expressed by context-free grammars alone, for example type validity and proper declaration of identifiers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] These rules can be formally expressed with attribute grammars.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The final phase is semantic parsing or analysis, which is working out the implications of the expression just validated and taking the appropriate action.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] In the case of a calculator or interpreter, the action is to evaluate the expression or program; a compiler, on the other hand, would generate some kind of code.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Attribute grammars can also be used to define these actions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The *task* of the parser is essentially to determine if and how the input can be derived from the start symbol of the grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] by expanding all alternative right-hand-sides of grammar rules.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] This is known as the primordial soup approach.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Very similar to sentence diagramming, primordial soup breaks down the constituencies of sentences.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] A parser can start with the input and attempt to rewrite it to the start symbol.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Intuitively, the parser attempts to locate the most basic elements, then the elements containing these, and so on.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] LL parsers and recursive-descent parser are examples of top-down parsers that cannot accommodate left recursive production rules.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Their algorithm is able to produce both left-most and right-most derivations of an input with regard to a given context-free grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] An important distinction with regard to parsers is whether a parser generates a *leftmost derivation* or a *rightmost derivation* (see context-free grammar).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] LL parsers will generate a leftmost derivation and LR parsers will generate a rightmost derivation (although usually in reverse).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Some *graphical parsing* algorithms have been designed for visual programming languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Parsers for visual languages are sometimes based on graph grammars.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Adaptive parsing algorithms have been used to construct "self-extending" natural language user interfaces.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] A simple parser implementation reads the entire input file, performs an intermediate computation or translation, and then writes the entire output file, such as in-memory multi-pass compilers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Lookahead establishes the maximum incoming tokens that a parser can use to decide which rule it should use.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Lookahead is especially relevant to LL, LR, and LALR parsers, where it is often explicitly indicated by affixing the lookahead to the algorithm name in parentheses, such as LALR(1).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Most programming languages, the primary target of parsers, are carefully defined in such a way that a parser with limited lookahead, typically one, can parse them, because parsers with limited lookahead are often more efficient.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] One important change to this trend came in 1990 when Terence Parr created ANTLR for his Ph.D. thesis, a parser generator for efficient LL(*k*) parsers, where *k* is any fixed value.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] LR parsers typically have only a few actions after seeing each token.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] They are shift (add this token to the stack for later reduction), reduce (pop tokens from the stack and form a syntactic construct), end, error (no known rule applies) or conflict (does not know whether to shift or reduce).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Most programming languages (except for a few such as APL and Smalltalk) and algebraic formulas give higher precedence to multiplication than addition, in which case the correct interpretation of the example above is 1 + (2 * 3).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Note that Rule4 above is a semantic rule.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] It is possible to rewrite the grammar to incorporate this into the syntax.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] However, not all such rules can be translated into syntax.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduces "1" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shift "+" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule1).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shift "2" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack element "2" to Expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, +, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule1.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shift "*" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule2).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shift "3" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack element "3" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, *, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule2.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The parse tree and resulting code from it is not correct according to language semantics.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack item 1 to simple Expression on input + based on rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The lookahead is +, so we are on path to E +, so we can reduce the stack to E.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shift + onto stack on input + in anticipation of rule1.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shift 2 onto stack on input 2 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack item 2 to Expression on input * based on rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The lookahead * expects only E before it.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Now stack has E + E and still the input is *.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] It has two choices now, either to shift based on rule2 or reduction based on rule1.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Since * has higher precedence than + based on rule4, we shift * onto stack in anticipation of rule2.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Shift 3 onto stack on input 3 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack item 3 to Expression after seeing end of input based on rule3.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack items E * E to E based on rule2.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] Reduce stack items E + E to E based on rule1.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] The parse tree generated is correct and simply more efficient than non-lookahead parsers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/parsing] This is the strategy followed in LALR parsers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] In computer science, a **recursive descent parser** is a kind of top-down parser built from a set of mutually recursive procedures (or a non-recursive equivalent) where each such procedure implements one of the nonterminals of the grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Thus the structure of the resulting program closely mirrors that of the grammar it recognizes.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] A *predictive parser* is a recursive descent parser that does not require backtracking.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Predictive parsing is possible only for the class of LL(*k*) grammars, which are the context-free grammars for which there exists some positive integer *k* that allows a recursive descent parser to decide which production to use by examining only the next *k* tokens of input.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] The LL(*k*) grammars therefore exclude all ambiguous grammars, as well as all grammars that contain left recursion.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Any context-free grammar can be transformed into an equivalent grammar that has no left recursion, but removal of left recursion does not always yield an LL(*k*) grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] A predictive parser runs in linear time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Recursive descent with backtracking is a technique that determines which production to use by trying each production in turn.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Recursive descent with backtracking is not limited to LL(*k*) grammars, but is not guaranteed to terminate unless the grammar is LL(*k*).
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Even when they terminate, parsers that use recursive descent with backtracking may require exponential time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Although predictive parsers are widely used, and are frequently chosen if writing a parser by hand, programmers often prefer to use a table-based parser produced by a parser generator, either for an LL(*k*) language or using an alternative parser, such as LALR or LR.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] This is particularly the case if a grammar is not in LL(*k*) form, as transforming the grammar to LL to make it suitable for predictive parsing is involved.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Predictive parsers can also be automatically generated, using tools like ANTLR.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Predictive parsers can be depicted using transition diagrams for each non-terminal symbol where the edges between the initial and the final states are labelled by the symbols (terminals and non-terminals) of the right side of the production rule.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Each nonterminal is defined by a rule in the grammar, except for *ident* and *number*, which are assumed to be implicitly defined.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] What follows is an implementation of a recursive descent parser for the above language in C.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] The parser reads in source code, and exits with an error message if the code fails to parse, exiting silently if the code parses correctly.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Notice how closely the predictive parser below mirrors the grammar above.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] There is a procedure for each nonterminal in the grammar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] Parsing descends in a top-down manner until the final nonterminal has been processed.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] The program fragment depends the functions `peeksym`, which peeks at the current symbol; `consumesym`, which consumes the symbol to move to the next; and `error`, which displays an error message.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] These functions are assumed to be provided by the lexer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/recursive-descent-parser] The C++ front-end of the Clang compiler contains a hand-written parser based on the recursive-descent parsing algorithm.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:nom-parser-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
